\begin{abstract}

Privacy-preserving range query over encrypted data has been widely studied, but existing schemes either suffer from high computational cost or leak structural information when applied to numerical IIoT sensor data. In this paper, we propose a Bitmap-Verified Conjunctive Range-cover Secure Aggregation (BVCRSA) framework that integrates attribute-based searchable encryption (ABSE) using BN128 bilinear pairings with lifted EC-ElGamal additive homomorphic encryption (AHE) over the NIST P-256 curve. The proposed scheme constructs a hierarchical encrypted index within a Trusted Execution Environment (TEE) at the edge, where each node maintains context-bound dual-layer tags, PRF-masked bitmaps, and encrypted aggregate summaries. Range queries are decomposed into a minimal set of disjoint interval nodes, achieving $O(\log |D_v|)$ query complexity. We design a lightweight structure-aware aggregation commitment for verifiable result integrity without zero-knowledge proofs. Formal security analysis proves payload confidentiality, adaptive search privacy, and access-control soundness. Experimental results show that BVCRSA achieves 0.03\,ms constant-time trapdoor generation and 6--12$\times$ faster query processing compared to six state-of-the-art schemes across database sizes up to $N = 100\text{K}$.

\end{abstract}

\begin{IEEEkeywords}
ABSE, Range Query, Data Aggregation, Edge Computing, IIoT Security, Leakage Control
