\section{Introduction}

With the rapid development of Industrial Internet of Things (IIoT) technology, large volumes of sensor data are continuously generated across smart manufacturing and critical infrastructure environments~\cite{ref1,ref2}. To reduce storage and computation costs, enterprises typically outsource these data to cloud servers. However, cloud servers are often considered semi-honest entities that may steal private information from outsourced data~\cite{ref3,ref4}. Therefore, sensor data should be encrypted before outsourcing. Nonetheless, encryption makes it difficult to perform efficient retrieval and analytics over the encrypted data.

Searchable encryption (SE) allows users to retrieve encrypted data without revealing plaintext to the cloud server~\cite{ref3,ref4}. Existing SE and attribute-based searchable encryption (ABSE) schemes~\cite{ref5,ref8,ref11} primarily focus on keyword-based retrieval and are not suited for IIoT applications where queries involve numerical range conditions. For example, operators may need to retrieve all temperature readings between $60^\circ$C and $80^\circ$C, or compute the average vibration level within a time window. Supporting both \emph{range queries} and \emph{aggregate analytics} over encrypted numerical data requires addressing several challenges simultaneously.

First, most existing privacy-preserving range query schemes suffer from efficiency or security limitations. Tong~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref14} and Gong~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref34} use kNN encryption for range queries, but kNN has been proven vulnerable to Known Plaintext Attacks (KPA). Liang~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref35} propose an encode-based range query (EPRQ+) using ASHVE, which achieves sublinear retrieval but does not support aggregation. Li~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref39} design a forward-secure DSSE for spatio-temporal queries (Trinity), but the SHVE-based construction incurs high overhead for wide-range queries. Zhang~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref37} propose MHRQ with revocable range queries for healthcare, yet their linear traversal results in $O(n)$ query complexity.

Second, existing schemes decouple data retrieval from computation. Privacy-preserving aggregation techniques based on homomorphic encryption~\cite{ref7,ref12} operate independently of search, requiring separate systems for query and analytics. No existing scheme provides a unified framework that simultaneously supports efficient range search, fine-grained access control, and secure aggregation.

Third, most ABSE-based systems~\cite{ref5,ref11} are limited to exact keyword matching and do not extend to numerical range queries or edge-assisted IIoT deployments.

To solve the above issues, we propose an Bitmap-Verified Conjunctive Range-cover Secure Aggregation (BVCRSA) framework. The key idea is to construct a hierarchical encrypted index within a TEE at the edge, where each node represents a value interval and maintains encrypted aggregate summaries. Range queries are decomposed into a minimal set of $O(\log |D_v|)$ disjoint interval nodes, enabling sublinear-in-domain-size query processing with $O(\\log |D_v|)$ complexity. We use ABSE with BN128 bilinear pairings for access-controlled search and lifted EC-ElGamal over NIST P-256 for additive homomorphic aggregation.

\noindent
\textbf{The main contributions of this paper are summarized as follows:}

\begin{itemize}

\item \textbf{Unified privacy-preserving search and analytics framework.}
We propose a TEE-assisted edge--cloud architecture that tightly integrates
attribute-based searchable encryption (ABSE) with additive homomorphic
encryption (AHE) to jointly support fine-grained access-controlled search
and secure aggregation over encrypted IIoT data. Unlike prior works that
decouple retrieval and computation, the proposed framework enables
query-driven analytics directly over encrypted indices and ciphertexts,
achieving end-to-end confidentiality while improving system efficiency
and coherence.

\item We propose a unified privacy-preserving framework that integrates ABSE with AHE to jointly support fine-grained access-controlled range search and secure aggregation over encrypted IIoT data.

\item We introduce the Bitmap-Verified Conjunctive Range-cover Secure Aggregation (BVCRSA), a hierarchical encrypted index with dual-layer context-bound tags, PRF-masked bitmaps, and path-consistent binding. BVCRSA decomposes range queries into $O(\log |D_v|)$ disjoint interval nodes for sublinear-in-domain-size query processing.

\item We embed lifted EC-ElGamal AHE within the BVCRSA structure to enable node-level homomorphic aggregation (sum, count, average) directly over encrypted data. A lightweight structure-aware aggregation commitment provides verifiable integrity without zero-knowledge proofs.

\item We implement BVCRSA using real BN128 bilinear pairings and NIST P-256 EC-ElGamal, and evaluate against six state-of-the-art schemes (EPBRQ, EPRQ+, MHRQ, Trinity, ABSE-Range, ECGRQ) across $N \in \{1\text{K}, 5\text{K}, 10\text{K}, 50\text{K}, 100\text{K}\}$. Experiments demonstrate 0.03\,ms constant trapdoor generation, 6--12$\times$ faster query processing, and robust performance under skewed $\mathcal{N}(70,10)$ sensor distributions.

\end{itemize}

The rest of this paper is organized as follows. Section~II reviews related work. Section~III presents the proposed scheme including the system model and detailed workflow. Section~IV provides formal security analysis. Section~V evaluates performance. Section~VI concludes the paper.




\section{Related Work}
\label{sec:related}

\subsection{Searchable Encryption and Attribute-Based Search}

Searchable Encryption (SE) enables querying over encrypted data without revealing plaintext information~\cite{ref3,ref4}. To enforce access control, ABSE was introduced~\cite{ref8}, enabling policy-constrained search. Subsequent works extend ABSE with hierarchical indexing~\cite{ref9}, hidden policies~\cite{ref15}, multi-keyword search~\cite{ref5,ref6,ref11}, blockchain auditability~\cite{ref17,ref18}, wildcard support~\cite{ref16,ref20}, and guessing attack resistance~\cite{ref30,ref32}. However, these schemes target keyword matching and do not support numerical range queries or aggregation.

\subsection{Privacy-Preserving Range Query}

Range queries over encrypted data have been widely studied. OPE/ORE~\cite{ref28} allow direct comparison but leak order information. Gong~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref34} use kNN encryption for Boolean range queries, but kNN is vulnerable to KPA~\cite{ref16}. Basudan~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref19} employ Oblivious Bloom Filters but introduce false positives.

Liang~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref35} propose EPRQ+ using ASHVE with a binary tree index, achieving sublinear retrieval. However, EPRQ+ does not support aggregation or access control. Liu~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref36} design volume-hiding SSE but at high system complexity. Zhang~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref37} propose MHRQ for healthcare with revocable range queries using CRQ matrix encryption, but incur $O(n)$ query complexity. Tang~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref38} extend to multi-dimensional ranges. Li~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref39} propose Trinity, a forward-secure DSSE for spatio-temporal queries using SHVE and Quotient Filters, but SHVE incurs high per-keyword cost for wide ranges. Li~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref41} propose ABSE-Range using LSSS matrix with 0,1-coding for attribute-based range search, but trapdoor cost grows linearly with range width due to per-block pairing tokens. Li~\textit{et al.}~\cite{ref44} propose ECGRQ using a privacy-preserving learned index for conjunctive geometric range queries, reducing search space via ML-based prediction, but learned-index accuracy degrades for wide ranges and retraining is required upon data updates.

Table~\ref{tab:functional_comparison} summarizes the functional comparison. Existing schemes either lack aggregation support, suffer from linear query complexity, or cannot enforce fine-grained access control.

\subsection{Privacy-Preserving Aggregation and Edge Architectures}

Homomorphic encryption~\cite{ref7} enables secure computation over encrypted data. Recent works improve efficiency through preprocessing~\cite{ref12} and edge-assisted architectures~\cite{ref21}. TEEs protect sensitive operations~\cite{ref23,ref25}. However, these techniques are applied independently from searchable encryption. No existing solution unifies efficient range search, ABSE-based access control, and homomorphic aggregation.



\section{Our Proposed Scheme}
This section presents the system model and the detailed workflow of the proposed scheme.

\subsection{System Model}

The proposed architecture consists of six primary entities, as
illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:system-model}. The system follows
a multi-layer IIoT–edge–cloud paradigm with clearly defined
trust boundaries.

\begin{enumerate}

\item \textbf{IIoT Sensor Nodes:}
Resource-constrained sensing devices that continuously capture
physical measurements (e.g., temperature, vibration).
Each sensor locally encrypts its data tuple using a symmetric
authenticated encryption scheme (e.g., AEAD) before transmission.
The encrypted tuple includes both the sensed numerical value
and associated contextual metadata (e.g., device ID, timestamp).

\item \textbf{TEE Manager and Enclave Balancer:}
These entities reside at the edge layer and are responsible for
secure orchestration of enclave execution. The TEE Manager
maintains a registry of active enclaves and performs remote
attestation to verify their integrity. The Enclave Balancer
dynamically distributes incoming processing tasks based on
real-time resource metrics, such as CPU utilization and Enclave
Page Cache (EPC) availability, ensuring load balancing,
fault tolerance, and scalable enclave utilization.

\item \textbf{Edge Node with TEE:}
The edge node acts as a trusted preprocessing and indexing
gateway. It is equipped with a Trusted Execution Environment
(TEE), within which all sensitive operations are securely
executed. These include decryption of incoming sensor data,
construction of the BVCRSA index, generation of context-bound
cryptographic tags, and maintenance of node-level encrypted
aggregate summaries. All plaintext data handling and indexing
logic are confined within the enclave boundary, preventing
leakage to the untrusted host environment.

\item \textbf{Cloud Server:}
The cloud server provides scalable storage and query processing
capabilities. It stores the encrypted BVCRSA structure, masked
bitmap indices, and homomorphic aggregate ciphertexts. During
query execution, the cloud performs secure matching over
encrypted indices and computes aggregate results using
homomorphic operations, without access to plaintext data or
secret keys. The cloud is assumed to be \emph{honest-but-curious}.

\item \textbf{Data User:}
An authorized entity that issues queries over encrypted data.
Each user possesses an attribute-based secret key for generating
secure trapdoors and a decryption key for recovering query
results. The user formulates range queries, generates
privacy-preserving tokens, and decrypts the returned aggregated
ciphertexts.

\item \textbf{Trusted Authority (TA):}
A fully trusted entity responsible for system initialization,
global parameter generation, and credential management.
The TA generates public parameters, issues attribute-based
secret keys to users, and manages system-wide cryptographic
material. It is assumed not to collude with the cloud or any
malicious entity.

\end{enumerate}

