\subsection{Threat Model}

We consider a realistic adversarial setting involving internal,
external, and network-based threats. The objective of the adversary is
to infer sensitive sensor values, recover query semantics, violate
access control, tamper with encrypted aggregates, or correlate
encrypted structures over time.

\subsubsection{Internal Threat: Honest-but-Curious Cloud Server}

The cloud server is assumed to be honest-but-curious. It correctly
executes the prescribed searchable matching, bitmap filtering, Merkle
proof generation, and homomorphic aggregation procedures, but may try
to infer sensitive information from the outsourced encrypted data and
observed queries. In particular, the cloud may attempt to: 1) recover
numerical sensor values from encrypted payloads or aggregate
ciphertexts; 2) infer query ranges, queried contexts, or user interests
by analyzing trapdoor tokens and access patterns; 3) perform frequency
or correlation analysis over encrypted BVCRSA nodes and bitmap
structures; and 4) omit, substitute, or reorder returned node summaries
during aggregation. However, the cloud does not possess the \ABSE
master secret key, the user attribute secret keys, the AHE decryption
key, or the TEE-protected plaintext data.

\subsubsection{External Threat: Unauthorized Users and Colluding Adversaries}

External adversaries include unauthorized users, malicious insiders
without sufficient attributes, and colluding users attempting to
escalate privileges. We consider the following threats. First, multiple
users may collude by combining their attribute keys in an attempt to
generate valid search tokens for policies that none of them can satisfy
individually. Second, an adversary may attempt to obtain unauthorized
access to encrypted data belonging to a different department, machine
group, or time interval. Third, an attacker may try to replay or reuse
previously issued trapdoors or intercept secret keys during insecure
delivery. The proposed framework mitigates these threats through
attribute-bound token generation, randomized trapdoor construction,
cryptographic binding between index and ciphertext, and secure key
distribution by the TA.

\subsubsection{Compromised Edge Software and Host-Level Adversaries}

The edge node is not assumed to be fully trusted at the host operating
system level. Instead, trust is placed only in the TEE enclave. We
consider adversaries who may control the edge host software, inspect
memory outside the enclave, manipulate the operating system, or observe
data entering and leaving the enclave. Such adversaries may attempt to
extract plaintext sensor readings, intermediate BVCRSA states, or
cryptographic material during preprocessing. The proposed design
mitigates this threat by confining all sensitive operations, including
sensor data decryption, context extraction, tag generation, masked
bitmap construction, homomorphic encryption, and aggregate maintenance,
within the TEE. Therefore, plaintext data and secret intermediate
states are never exposed outside the enclave boundary.

\subsubsection{Network Threats: Eavesdropping, Interception, and Replay}

Since data flows from sensors to the edge and then from the edge to the
cloud, the system must withstand network-level attacks. We consider
man-in-the-middle adversaries that intercept, modify, inject, or replay
messages over these communication channels. In particular, an attacker
may attempt to tamper with sensor data in transit, correlate repeated
ciphertexts, or replay stale encrypted tuples and query tokens. To
mitigate these threats, sensor-to-edge communication is protected using
authenticated symmetric encryption, while encrypted indexing and
aggregation metadata are protected by pseudorandomized tag derivation,
masked bitmap structures, randomized trapdoors, Merkle-proof-based
verification, and aggregation commitments.

\subsubsection{Assumptions and Security Boundary}

We assume that the Trusted Authority is fully trusted, the underlying
cryptographic primitives are secure, and the TEE provides integrity and
confidentiality for code and data executing inside the enclave. We do
not consider physical attacks on sensors, denial-of-service attacks, or
side-channel attacks against the TEE hardware. The cloud server and
network adversaries may observe bounded leakage, such as access pattern
information, node access frequency, and the number of BVCRSA nodes
involved in a query, but they cannot learn plaintext sensor values,
exact query semantics, or unauthorized aggregate results beyond this
leakage profile.

\subsection{System Process}

As illustrated in Fig.~\ref{fig:workflow}, the proposed framework
operates in five phases. In Phase~1, the TA initializes cryptographic
parameters and distributes keys. In Phase~2, the edge TEE decrypts
incoming sensor data, constructs the BVCRSA index (Fig.~\ref{fig:scrat-tree}),
and outsources encrypted structures to the cloud. In Phase~3, an
authorized user decomposes a range query into canonical BVCRSA interval
nodes and generates ABSE trapdoor tokens. In Phase~4, the cloud
performs ABSE matching, bitmap filtering, and homomorphic aggregation
over matched nodes. In Phase~5, the user verifies result integrity
via Merkle proofs and aggregation commitments, then decrypts the
aggregate ciphertexts using EC-ElGamal.

