\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 1: System Setup}}

The system setup phase is executed by a trusted authority (TA)
to initialize global cryptographic parameters. Let $\lambda$
denote the security parameter. The TA defines the attribute
universe $\mathcal{U}$ for fine-grained access control.

\textbf{Step 1: Initialization of the ABSE system.}
The TA runs the ABSE setup algorithm:
\begin{equation}
(PP, MSK) \leftarrow \textsf{ABSE.Setup}(1^\lambda),
\end{equation}
where $PP$ includes the bilinear group parameters
$(p,\mathbb{G}_1,\mathbb{G}_T,e,g)$ and associated hash functions,
and $MSK$ is the master secret key retained by the TA.

\textbf{Step 2: Attribute-based key generation.}
For each authorized user with attribute set
$A \subseteq \mathcal{U}$, the TA generates:
\begin{equation}
SK_A \leftarrow \textsf{ABSE.KeyGen}(MSK, A),
\end{equation}
which enables the user to generate valid trapdoors for
authorized search queries.

\textbf{Step 3: Initialization of lifted EC-ElGamal AHE.}
To support secure aggregation over encrypted sensor values, the TA
initializes a lifted EC-ElGamal additive homomorphic encryption scheme
over the NIST P-256 elliptic curve. Let $(\mathbb{G}, G, p)$ denote
the cyclic group of prime order $p$ generated by the base point $G$
on the P-256 curve.

The TA generates the key pair as follows:
\begin{align}
x &\xleftarrow{\$} \mathbb{Z}_p^*, \\
P &= xG, \\
(pk_{AHE}, sk_{AHE}) &= (P, x).
\end{align}

The lifted EC-ElGamal encryption of a sensor value $v \in \mathbb{Z}$
is defined as:
\begin{equation}
\textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, v) = (C_1, C_2) = (rG,\; vG + rP),
\end{equation}
where $r \xleftarrow{\$} \mathbb{Z}_p^*$ is fresh randomness.
The ``lifted'' construction maps $v$ to the curve point $vG$,
enabling additive homomorphism via elliptic curve point addition:
\begin{equation}
\textsf{Enc}(v_1) + \textsf{Enc}(v_2)
= \big((r_1+r_2)G,\; (v_1+v_2)G + (r_1+r_2)P\big)
= \textsf{Enc}(v_1+v_2).
\end{equation}

Decryption recovers the embedded point $vG$:
\begin{equation}
vG = C_2 - x \cdot C_1,
\end{equation}
and the plaintext integer $v$ is recovered using the
Baby-step Giant-step (BSGS) algorithm over the precomputed
table $\{jG : 0 \leq j < \lceil\sqrt{v_{max}}\rceil\}$,
where $v_{max}$ denotes the maximum expected aggregate value.
This yields $O(\sqrt{v_{max}})$ precomputation and $O(\sqrt{v_{max}})$
decryption time, which is efficient for bounded IIoT sensor domains.

The public key $P$ is distributed to all edge enclaves for
encryption, while the private scalar $x$ is securely provided
only to authorized data users for result decryption.

\textbf{Step 4: Initialization of cryptographic primitives.}
The TA defines the following primitives:

\begin{itemize}
\item A pseudorandom function (PRF):
\begin{equation}
F_{K_s} : \{0,1\}^* \rightarrow \{0,1\}^{\lambda},
\end{equation}
where $K_s$ is a secret seed shared with authorized users for
deterministic tag derivation.

\item A hash-to-group function:
\begin{equation}
H_g : \{0,1\}^* \rightarrow \mathbb{G}_1,
\end{equation}

\item A collision-resistant hash function:
\begin{equation}
H : \{0,1\}^* \rightarrow \{0,1\}^{\lambda}.
\end{equation}
\end{itemize}

The function $H_g(\cdot)$ is used for BVCRSA node tag generation,
while $F_{K_s}(\cdot)$ ensures pseudorandomization to mitigate
frequency analysis and token linkage.

\textbf{Step 5: Secure channel establishment for data ingestion.}
Each sensor node $i$ is assigned a unique symmetric key derived as:
\begin{equation}
K_{AES}^{(i)} = \textsf{KDF}(K_{master}, ID_i),
\end{equation}
where $K_{master}$ is a master secret maintained by the TA.
Sensor data tuples $D = (m,k,t,v)$ are encrypted using AEAD:
\begin{equation}
CT_{AES}^{(i)} = \textsf{AES\text{-}GCM.Enc}(K_{AES}^{(i)}, D),
\end{equation}
ensuring both confidentiality and integrity during transmission
to the edge node.

\textbf{Step 6: Initialization of binding and masking mechanisms.}
To ensure integrity between index structures and encrypted values,
a cryptographic binding is defined as:
\begin{equation}
\sigma = H(\tau_u \parallel CT_v),
\end{equation}
where $\tau_u$ denotes the BVCRSA node tag and $CT_v$ is the
encrypted sensor value.

Additionally, bitmap masking is supported via:
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{B}_u = B_u \oplus R_u,
\end{equation}
where $R_u$ is a pseudorandom mask derived from $F_{K_s}(\cdot)$.

The TA publishes the public parameters $PP$ and $pk_{AHE}$.
The secrets $MSK$, $K_s$, and $K_{master}$ remain confidential
at the TA, while $sk_{AHE}$ and $SK_A$ are securely distributed
to authorized users.

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 2: Adaptive BVCRSA Construction and Secure Data Encoding}}

This phase is executed at the edge within a Trusted Execution
Environment (TEE) to transform incoming \IIoT sensor data into
a novel encrypted index structure termed \emph{Adaptive
Context-bound BVCRSA (BVCRSA)}. Unlike conventional static
interval trees, BVCRSA dynamically adapts its structure
based on data distribution and contextual attributes,
enabling efficient and privacy-preserving range query
processing.

\begin{algorithm}[h]
\caption{TEE-Based Secure BVCRSA Construction}
\label{alg:tee_scrat}
\begin{algorithmic}[1]
\item[\textbf{Input:}] $CT_{AES}^{(i)}$, $K_{AES}^{(i)}$, $pk_{AHE}$, $PP$
\item[\textbf{Output:}] $\{CT_u^{tag}, \widetilde{B}_u, CT_v, Agg_u, \sigma_u\}$

\State \textit{// Step 1: Secure ingestion inside TEE (cf.\ Algorithm~\ref{alg:tee_scrat})}
\State $D \leftarrow \textsf{AES\text{-}GCM.Dec}(K_{AES}^{(i)}, CT_{AES}^{(i)})$
\State Parse $D = (m,k,t,v)$, $ctx \leftarrow (m,k,t)$
\State \textit{// Step 2: Adaptive BVCRSA path construction}
\State Identify $\mathcal{P}_v = \{u \mid v \in I_u\}$

\For{each $u \in \mathcal{P}_v$}
    \State \textit{// Step 3: Dual-layer tag generation}
    \State $\tau_u^{struct} \leftarrow H_g(l_u \parallel r_u)$
    \State $\tau_u^{ctx} \leftarrow F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel u)$
    \State $\tau_u \leftarrow H_g(\tau_u^{struct} \parallel \tau_u^{ctx})$

    \State \textit{// Step 4: Bitmap masking}
    \State $\widetilde{B}_u \leftarrow \hat{B}_u \oplus F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel u)$

    \State \textit{// Step 5: ABSE encryption}
    \State $CT_u^{tag} \leftarrow \textsf{ABSE.Enc}(PP, \tau_u, \mathcal{P})$

    \State \textit{// Step 6: Homomorphic encoding}
    \State $CT_v \leftarrow \textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, v)$
    \State $Agg_u \leftarrow Agg_u + CT_v$ \Comment{EC point addition}

    \State \textit{// Step 7: Path-consistent binding}
    \State $\sigma_u \leftarrow H(\tau_u \parallel CT_v \parallel \sigma_{parent(u)})$
\EndFor

\State \Return $\{CT_u^{tag}, \widetilde{B}_u, CT_v, Agg_u, \sigma_u\}$
\end{algorithmic}
\end{algorithm}

\textbf{Step 1: Secure Data Ingestion.}
Within the enclave, the encrypted tuple is decrypted as:
\begin{align}
D &= \textsf{AES\text{-}GCM.Dec}(K_{AES}^{(i)}, CT_{AES}^{(i)}), \\
D &= (m, k, t, v), \quad ctx = (m, k, t),
\end{align}
ensuring that all plaintext processing remains confined within
the TEE boundary. As shown in Algorithm~\ref{alg:tee_scrat}, the enclave first decrypts the incoming ciphertext and extracts the contextual tuple $(m,k,t,v)$ for subsequent processing.

\textbf{Step 2: Adaptive BVCRSA Construction.}
Let $D_v = [v_{min}, v_{max}]$ denote the value domain.
BVCRSA organizes data into context-aware interval nodes
$u$ with ranges $I_u = [l_u, r_u]$, where the interval
granularity is dynamically adjusted based on observed data
distribution and contextual similarity. For each incoming
value $v$, the enclave identifies a minimal adaptive path:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{P}_v = \{ u \mid v \in I_u \},
\end{equation}
and updates all nodes along this path, including aggregate
states and index metadata. This adaptive construction reduces
unnecessary node expansions and ensures efficient updates with
logarithmic complexity in expectation.

\textbf{Step 3: Dual-Layer Context-Bound Tag Generation.}
Each node generates two cryptographically linked tags to
capture both structural and contextual information:
\begin{align}
\tau_u^{struct} &= H_g(l_u \parallel r_u), \\
\tau_u^{ctx} &= F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel u),
\end{align}
which are combined as:
\begin{equation}
\tau_u = H_g(\tau_u^{struct} \parallel \tau_u^{ctx}).
\end{equation}
This dual-layer construction ensures that identical intervals
across different contexts remain unlinkable, while preserving
deterministic indexing within the same context, thereby
preventing cross-context inference and frequency leakage.

\textbf{Step 4: Leakage-Aware Bitmap Encoding.}
Each node maintains a compressed membership vector
$\hat{B}_u$ that encodes the presence of data records
associated with node $u$. To protect against direct
membership disclosure and access-pattern leakage, the
bitmap is masked using a pseudorandom function:
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{B}_u = \hat{B}_u \oplus F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel u),
\end{equation}
where the mask is deterministically derived from the
context and node identifier. This design enables efficient
bitwise filtering during query processing while ensuring
that the underlying membership information remains
computationally hidden, thereby mitigating frequency and
correlation-based inference attacks.

\textbf{Step 5: Policy-Protected Index Encryption.}
Each node tag is encrypted under an access policy
$\mathcal{P}$ using the ABSE scheme:
\begin{equation}
CT_u^{tag} = \textsf{ABSE.Enc}(PP, \tau_u, \mathcal{P}),
\end{equation}
such that only users whose attribute sets satisfy
$\mathcal{P}$ can generate valid trapdoors for matching.
This mechanism enforces fine-grained, cryptographically
protected access control directly at the index level,
preventing unauthorized search over encrypted data.

\textbf{Step 6: Homomorphic Aggregation Encoding.}
Sensor values are encrypted using lifted EC-ElGamal:
\begin{equation}
CT_v = \textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, v) = (r_v G,\; vG + r_v P),
\end{equation}
where $r_v \xleftarrow{\$} \mathbb{Z}_p^*$ provides semantic
security (identical values produce distinct ciphertexts).
A count ciphertext is similarly generated:
\begin{equation}
CT_{cnt} = \textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, 1).
\end{equation}

Each BVCRSA node $u$ maintains encrypted aggregates updated
via elliptic curve point addition:
\begin{align}
Agg_u &\leftarrow Agg_u + CT_v
= \Big(\sum_i C_1^{(i)},\; \sum_i C_2^{(i)}\Big), \\
Cnt_u &\leftarrow Cnt_u + CT_{cnt}.
\end{align}

By the additive homomorphic property of lifted EC-ElGamal,
these operations correspond to:
\begin{equation}
\textsf{Dec}(Agg_u) = \sum_{x \in Desc(u)} x,
\quad
\textsf{Dec}(Cnt_u) = |Desc(u)|,
\end{equation}
enabling sum, count, and average computations directly over
encrypted node summaries without accessing plaintext data.
\textbf{Step 7: Path-Consistent Binding.}
A recursive hash binding is applied:
\begin{equation}
\sigma_u = H(\tau_u \parallel CT_v \parallel \sigma_{parent(u)}),
\end{equation}
ensuring integrity across the BVCRSA hierarchy.

\textbf{Step 8: Secure Outsourcing.}
The encrypted structures
\[
\{CT_u^{tag}, \widetilde{B}_u, CT_v, Agg_u, \sigma_u\}
\]
are outsourced to the cloud server. We adopt a blockchain-based ledger rather than a simple append-only log to provide immutable public auditability without requiring a trusted third party.

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 3: Trapdoor Generation}}

When an authorized user issues a range query, a secure
trapdoor is generated to encode query constraints while
preserving query privacy. The trapdoor consists of a set
of cryptographic tokens corresponding to a minimal set of
BVCRSA interval nodes.

\textbf{Step 1: Query specification.}
A range query is defined as:
\begin{equation}
Q = (m,k,t_q,[a,b]),
\end{equation}
where $m$ denotes the machine identifier, $k$ the sensor
attribute, $t_q$ the query time context, and $[a,b]$ the
target value range.

\textbf{Step 2: Canonical interval decomposition.}
The user computes a minimal interval cover over BVCRSA:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{C}(a,b) = \{u_1,u_2,\dots,u_{\ell}\},
\end{equation}
such that:
\begin{equation}
[a,b] \subseteq \bigcup_{i=1}^{\ell} I_{u_i},
\end{equation}
where $\ell = O(\log |D_v|)$.

\textbf{Step 3: Context-bound dual-tag reconstruction.}
For each node $u_i \in \mathcal{C}(a,b)$, the user reconstructs:
\begin{equation}
ctx = (m,k,t_q),
\end{equation}
and derives:
\begin{align}
\tau^{struct}_{u_i} &= H_g(l_{u_i} \parallel r_{u_i}), \\
\tau^{ctx}_{u_i} &= F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel l_{u_i} \parallel r_{u_i}),
\end{align}
which are combined into:
\begin{equation}
\tau_{u_i} = H_g(\tau^{struct}_{u_i} \parallel \tau^{ctx}_{u_i}).
\end{equation}
This reconstruction is consistent with the index generation
process, ensuring correct matching while preserving
context isolation.

\textbf{Step 4: Token randomization.}
To achieve query unlinkability, the user samples
$r_i \xleftarrow{\$} \mathbb{Z}_p$ and computes:
\begin{equation}
\tau'_{u_i} = \tau_{u_i} \cdot g^{r_i}.
\end{equation}
This randomized encoding ensures that identical queries
produce computationally unlinkable trapdoors, while still
allowing alignment with encrypted index entries via the
auxiliary component $g^{r_i}$.

\textbf{Step 5: Attribute-bound token generation.}
Using the attribute-based secret key $SK_A$, the user computes:
\begin{equation}
Tok_i = \textsf{ABSE.TokenGen}(SK_A, \tau'_{u_i}),
\end{equation}
binding each token to both the query condition and the
user’s attribute set, thereby enforcing fine-grained
search authorization.

\textbf{Step 6: Trapdoor construction.}
The final trapdoor is defined as:
\begin{equation}
T_Q = \{(Tok_i, g^{r_i})\}_{i=1}^{\ell}.
\end{equation}
Since $\ell = O(\log |D_v|)$, both trapdoor size and
generation cost remain logarithmic.


The trapdoor construction reveals only the number of queried
intervals and access patterns over BVCRSA nodes, while hiding
the exact query range, contextual attributes, and linkage
between repeated queries under standard PRF and ABSE security
assumptions.

\subsubsection*{\textbf{Phase 4: Secure Range Query Processing}}

Upon receiving the trapdoor $T_Q$, the cloud server performs
privacy-preserving range query evaluation over the encrypted
BVCRSA index. The goal is to identify interval nodes corresponding
to the canonical range cover while enforcing access control and
preserving query privacy.

The cloud observes only bounded leakage characterized by:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}} =
\left(
\ell,\;
\textsf{AccessPattern},\;
\textsf{NodeFrequency}
\right),
\end{equation}
where $\ell = |\mathcal{C}(a,b)|$. This leakage reveals only
structural access patterns over BVCRSA nodes, while hiding the
exact query range, contextual attributes, and plaintext data.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 1: Token-to-node matching under encrypted indices.}
%--------------------------------------------------

Let the trapdoor be:
\begin{equation}
T_Q = \{(Tok_i, g^{r_i})\}_{i=1}^{\ell}.
\end{equation}

Each token corresponds to a randomized encoding of a BVCRSA node
in the canonical cover $\mathcal{C}(a,b)$. For each node $u$,
the cloud evaluates:
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Match}(Tok_i, CT_u^{tag}) =
\textsf{ABSE.Test}(PP, Tok_i, CT_u^{tag}).
\end{equation}

The auxiliary component $g^{r_i}$ enables consistent alignment
with encrypted tags under randomization, ensuring correctness
without revealing the underlying deterministic tag.

The candidate node set is:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_Q =
\Big\{
u \;\Big|\;
\exists\, Tok_i \in T_Q :
\textsf{ABSE.Test}(PP, Tok_i, CT_u^{tag}) = 1
\Big\}.
\end{equation}

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 2: Leakage-aware bitmap filtering.}
%--------------------------------------------------

To further prune the candidate set, the cloud applies masked
bitmap filtering. The query-side masked bitmap is reconstructed
as:
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{B}_Q = F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel \mathcal{C}(a,b)),
\end{equation}
which is consistent with the masking used during index construction.

For each node $u \in \mathcal{U}_Q$, the cloud evaluates:
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Filter}(u) =
\widetilde{B}_u \wedge \widetilde{B}_Q \neq \mathbf{0}.
\end{equation}

The refined node set is:
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{U}_Q^{*} =
\{ u \in \mathcal{U}_Q \mid \mathsf{Filter}(u) = 1 \}.
\end{equation}

This step reduces computational overhead while introducing
only minimal additional leakage due to masked representations.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 3: Homomorphic aggregation over BVCRSA nodes.}
%--------------------------------------------------

For all nodes $u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}$, the cloud computes the
aggregate via elliptic curve point addition:
\begin{equation}
CT_{agg} =
\sum_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} Agg_u,
\end{equation}
where $\sum$ denotes component-wise EC point addition of the
ciphertext pairs $(C_1, C_2)$.

By the additive homomorphic property of lifted EC-ElGamal,
this operation corresponds to:
\begin{equation}
CT_{agg} = \textsf{Enc}\left(\sum_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} v_u\right),
\end{equation}
where $v_u$ represents the aggregate of values at node $u$.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 4: Result generation.}
%--------------------------------------------------

The cloud returns:
\begin{equation}
R_Q = (CT_{agg}, \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}),
\end{equation}
to the data user for decryption and verification.


The overall query processing cost is:
\begin{equation}
O(\ell + |\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}|),
\end{equation}
where $\ell = O(\log |D_v|)$.

\subsubsection{\textbf{Phase 5: Homomorphic Aggregation and Verifiable Result Recovery}}

After identifying the refined node set $\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}$ in
Phase~4, the cloud performs secure aggregation over encrypted
BVCRSA node summaries without accessing plaintext values, while
ensuring verifiable correctness of the computation.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 1: Verified node-level retrieval with structural binding.}
%--------------------------------------------------

For each node $u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}$, the cloud retrieves:
\begin{equation}
\{Agg_u , Cnt_u, \sigma_u, \pi_u\},
\end{equation}
where $\pi_u$ denotes the structural proof (e.g., Merkle path)
associated with node $u$.

The user verifies:
\begin{equation}
\mathsf{Verify}(Root, u, Agg_u, Cnt_u, \pi_u) = 1,
\end{equation}
ensuring membership correctness, and checks path-consistent binding:
\begin{equation}
\sigma_u \stackrel{?}{=} H(\tau_u \parallel CT_v \parallel \sigma_{parent(u)}).
\end{equation}

Only nodes satisfying both conditions are accepted, ensuring
authenticity and structural consistency of all inputs.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 2: Homomorphic aggregation over disjoint BVCRSA nodes.}
%--------------------------------------------------

Since nodes in $\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}$ form a minimal disjoint interval cover:
\begin{equation}
\forall u,v \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*},\; u \neq v : I_u \cap I_v = \emptyset,
\end{equation}
the cloud computes via EC point addition:
\begin{equation}
CT_{sum} = \sum_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} Agg_u,
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
CT_{count} = \sum_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} Cnt_u.
\end{equation}

By homomorphic correctness:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Dec}(x, CT_{sum}) &= \sum_{x \in R_Q} x, \\
\textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Dec}(x, CT_{count}) &= |R_Q|.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 3: Structure-aware aggregation commitment (Novelty).}
%--------------------------------------------------

To guarantee completeness and soundness of the aggregation,
the cloud computes a structure-aware commitment:
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{agg} =
H\Big(
Root \parallel
\{u\}_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} \parallel
CT_{sum} \parallel CT_{count}
\Big).
\end{equation}

The user verifies:
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{agg} \stackrel{?}{=}
H\Big(
Root \parallel
\{u\}_{u \in \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}} \parallel
CT_{sum} \parallel CT_{count}
\Big).
\end{equation}

This commitment ensures:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Completeness:} No valid node is omitted,
\item \textbf{Soundness:} No invalid node is included,
\item \textbf{Consistency:} Aggregation matches BVCRSA structure.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Novelty:}
Unlike conventional verifiable computation approaches that rely
on expensive zero-knowledge proofs, this scheme introduces a
lightweight, structure-aware commitment tightly coupled with
BVCRSA, enabling efficient and verifiable homomorphic aggregation.

%--------------------------------------------------
\textbf{Step 4: Result transmission.}
%--------------------------------------------------

The cloud returns:
\begin{equation}
(CT_{sum}, CT_{count}, \Pi_{agg}, \mathcal{U}_Q^{*}).
\end{equation}

The cloud learns no plaintext values and only observes bounded
aggregation leakage captured by $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}$.

\textbf{Step 5: Result recovery via EC-ElGamal decryption.}
%--------------------------------------------------

Upon receiving the aggregated ciphertexts, the user applies
EC-ElGamal decryption using private scalar $x = sk_{AHE}$:
\begin{align}
S \cdot G &= C_2^{(sum)} - x \cdot C_1^{(sum)}, \\
N \cdot G &= C_2^{(count)} - x \cdot C_1^{(count)},
\end{align}
where $(C_1^{(sum)}, C_2^{(sum)}) = CT_{sum}$ and
$(C_1^{(count)}, C_2^{(count)}) = CT_{count}$.

The plaintext integers $Sum$ and $Count$ are recovered from
the curve points $S \cdot G$ and $N \cdot G$ using the
Baby-step Giant-step (BSGS) algorithm:
\begin{equation}
Sum = \textsf{BSGS}(S \cdot G),
\quad
Count = \textsf{BSGS}(N \cdot G),
\end{equation}
where the BSGS table $\{jG : 0 \leq j < m\}$ with
$m = \lceil\sqrt{v_{max}}\rceil$ is precomputed once during
user initialization. For IIoT sensor data with values in
$[0, 100]$ and up to $N = 5000$ records, the maximum aggregate
is bounded by $v_{max} = 500{,}000$, requiring a table of
$\lceil\sqrt{500{,}000}\rceil = 708$ entries.

If the average is required:
\begin{equation}
Avg = \frac{Sum}{Count}.
\end{equation}

Since aggregation operates over BVCRSA nodes:
\begin{equation}
|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}| = O(\log |D_v|),
\end{equation}
ensuring scalable and efficient query processing.
This verification mechanism provides $O(1)$ commitment validation
with respect to query size, significantly reducing verification
overhead compared to proof-based approaches.


\section{Security Analysis}
\label{sec:security}

We analyze the security of the proposed TEE-assisted BVCRSA-based
ABSE framework against probabilistic polynomial-time (PPT)
adversaries. The scheme combines searchable encryption, additive
homomorphic encryption, masked index structures, and TEE-assisted edge
processing. Accordingly, the security analysis must address four
properties simultaneously: \emph{(i)} payload confidentiality,
\emph{(ii)} search and index privacy under adaptive queries,
\emph{(iii)} resistance against a compromised edge host, and
\emph{(iv)} verifiable correctness of outsourced aggregation.

Let $\lambda$ denote the security parameter.

\subsection{Security Assumptions}

The security of the proposed scheme relies on the following standard
assumptions.

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{AHE Security:}
The additive homomorphic encryption scheme is IND-CPA secure. Hence,
ciphertexts of sensor values and aggregated ciphertexts reveal no
plaintext information to any PPT adversary without the decryption key.

\item \textbf{ABSE Security:}
The underlying attribute-based searchable encryption scheme is
adaptively secure against chosen-keyword/chosen-query attacks
(IND-CKA secure), and enforces policy-constrained token generation.

\item \textbf{PRF Security:}
The pseudorandom function $F_{K_s}$ is secure, so its outputs are
computationally indistinguishable from random strings to any PPT
adversary that does not know $K_s$.

\item \textbf{Hash Assumptions:}
The hash function $H(\cdot)$ is collision-resistant, and the
hash-to-group function $H_g(\cdot)$ is modeled as a random oracle
when required in the proof of tag indistinguishability.

\item \textbf{Merkle Integrity:}
The hash function used in the Merkle authentication structure is
collision-resistant, ensuring sound membership verification.

\item \textbf{TEE Assumption:}
The Trusted Execution Environment guarantees confidentiality and
integrity of code and data inside the enclave. An adversary controlling
the host operating system cannot access enclave memory, alter enclave
execution, or forge attestation evidence.

\item \textbf{Authenticated Channel Security:}
The AEAD scheme used for device-to-edge protection (e.g.,
AES-GCM) provides confidentiality and integrity for sensor tuples
during transmission.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Adversarial Model}

We consider the following adversaries.

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Cloud Adversary $\mathcal{A}_{cloud}$:}
An honest-but-curious cloud server that faithfully executes search and
aggregation protocols but attempts to infer sensitive information from
encrypted indices, trapdoors, ciphertexts, access patterns, and
returned aggregates.

\item \textbf{Edge Adversary $\mathcal{A}_{edge}$:}
A strong adversary controlling the edge host software stack,
including the OS, scheduler, memory outside the enclave, and I/O
channels. However, it cannot break TEE security.

\item \textbf{External Adversary $\mathcal{A}_{ext}$:}
An unauthorized user or colluding set of users that attempts to
generate valid search tokens without satisfying the required access
policy, infer query semantics, or tamper with returned results.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Leakage Function}

As in most practical searchable-encryption systems, the proposed
scheme does not hide all side information. Instead, it reveals only
bounded leakage captured by the function
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}} = \big(&
|\mathcal{C}(a,b)|,\;
\textsf{AccessPattern},\;
\textsf{NodeFrequency},\\
&\textsf{QueryRepetition},\;
\textsf{BitmapPattern},\\
&\textsf{BitmapIntersection},\;
\textsf{NodeFreqDist}
\big)
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where:
\begin{itemize}
\item $|\mathcal{C}(a,b)|$ denotes the number of canonical BVCRSA nodes
used to cover the queried range,
\item $\textsf{AccessPattern}$ denotes which encrypted BVCRSA nodes are
accessed during query execution,
\item $\textsf{NodeFrequency}$ denotes how frequently individual nodes are matched
across queries,
\item $\textsf{QueryRepetition}$ captures whether two queries induce the
same observable access behavior,
\item $\textsf{BitmapPattern}$ denotes the masked filtering behavior
induced by bitmap operations,
\item $\textsf{BitmapIntersection}$ captures the intersection pattern
between query-side and index-side masked bitmaps, revealing partial
overlap information across filtered node sets, and
\item $\textsf{NodeFreqDist}$ captures the frequency distribution of
node accesses over time, revealing which BVCRSA nodes are
disproportionately queried.
\end{itemize}

Importantly, the leakage function excludes plaintext values, exact
query intervals, contextual attributes, unmasked membership vectors,
and intermediate TEE states.

\subsection{Security Definitions}

\textbf{Definition 1 (Payload Confidentiality).}
The scheme achieves payload confidentiality if no PPT adversary can
distinguish between encryptions of two equal-length plaintext sensor
values with more than negligible advantage.

\textbf{Definition 2 (Adaptive Search Privacy).}
The scheme is adaptively IND-CKA secure if no PPT adversary can
distinguish the trapdoors of two adaptively chosen queries whose
leakage under $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}$ is identical.

\textbf{Definition 3 (Edge Security).}
The scheme is edge-secure if a PPT adversary controlling the edge host
learns no plaintext tuple, no unmasked BVCRSA state, and no secret
intermediate value beyond negligible probability.

\textbf{Definition 4 (Access-Control Soundness).}
The scheme is access-sound if no PPT adversary whose attribute set does
not satisfy policy $\mathcal{P}$ can generate a token that passes the
ABSE matching test for an index encrypted under $\mathcal{P}$.

\textbf{Definition 5 (Verifiable Aggregation).}
The scheme provides verifiable aggregation if any modification,
omission, duplication, or injection of BVCRSA node aggregates is
detected with overwhelming probability.

\subsection{Theorem 1: Payload Confidentiality}

\textbf{Statement.}
Under the IND-CPA security of the AHE scheme, the confidentiality of
the AEAD channel, and the confidentiality guarantee of the TEE, the
proposed scheme preserves the secrecy of sensor values against any PPT
adversary, including $\mathcal{A}_{cloud}$ and $\mathcal{A}_{edge}$.

\textbf{Proof.}
We prove the claim through a standard hybrid argument.

\textbf{Game 0 (Real Execution).}
The adversary observes all real protocol artifacts, including encrypted
sensor values $\{CT_v\}$, encrypted node aggregates $\{Agg_u,Cnt_u\}$,
masked bitmaps, encrypted tags, and trapdoors.

\textbf{Game 1 (AHE Challenge Replacement).}
Replace the encryption of a target value $v$ with the challenger output
\begin{equation}
CT_v = \textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, v_b), \qquad b \in \{0,1\}.
\end{equation}
By IND-CPA security of EC-ElGamal,
\begin{equation}
\left|
\Pr[b'=b]-\frac{1}{2}
\right| \leq \epsilon_1(\lambda).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game 2 (Aggregate Simulation).}
Replace node aggregates by homomorphic encryptions of challenge values.
Since
\begin{equation}
Agg_u = \prod_{x \in Desc(u)} CT_x,
\end{equation}
and homomorphic aggregation operates only on ciphertexts, the
adversary gains no additional information beyond the underlying AHE
ciphertexts. Thus the distinguishing gap changes by at most
$\epsilon_2(\lambda)$.

\textbf{Game 3 (TEE Isolation).}
Replace all enclave-internal computations by an ideal black-box
functionality. Since plaintext tuples are decrypted, parsed, indexed,
and aggregated only inside the TEE, the edge adversary cannot observe
intermediate states unless it breaks enclave confidentiality. Hence the
difference between Games 2 and 3 is bounded by $\epsilon_3(\lambda)$.

\textbf{Game 4 (Simulation).}
Replace all target ciphertexts with random ciphertexts consistent with
the leakage profile. The adversary’s total distinguishing advantage is
bounded by
\begin{equation}
\left|
\Pr[b'=b]-\frac{1}{2}
\right|
\leq
\epsilon_1(\lambda)+\epsilon_2(\lambda)+\epsilon_3(\lambda),
\end{equation}
which is negligible.

Therefore, payload confidentiality holds.


\subsection{Theorem 2: Adaptive Search and Index Privacy (IND-CKA)}

\textbf{Statement.}
Assuming the security of $F_{K_s}$, the random-oracle behavior of
$H_g$, and the adaptive IND-CKA security of the ABSE scheme, the
proposed construction achieves adaptive search privacy with leakage
$\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}$.

\textbf{Security Game.}
The challenger runs setup and returns public parameters $PP$. The
adversary may adaptively issue:
\begin{itemize}
\item key-generation queries for attribute sets not violating the
challenge policy restrictions,
\item trapdoor queries for arbitrary non-challenge queries, and
\item finally a challenge on two queries $Q_0,Q_1$ such that
\begin{equation}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}(Q_0)=\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}(Q_1).
\end{equation}
The challenger flips $b \leftarrow \{0,1\}$ and returns the challenge
trapdoor $T_{Q_b}$.
\end{itemize}
The adversary outputs $b'$, and its advantage is
\begin{equation}
Adv_{\mathcal{A}}^{IND\text{-}CKA}
=
\left|
\Pr[b'=b]-\frac{1}{2}
\right|.
\end{equation}

\textbf{Proof.}
We define a sequence of hybrid games.

\textbf{Game 0 (Real Game).}
Trapdoors are generated honestly using
\begin{equation}
\tau_u^{ctx}=F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel l_u \parallel r_u),
\qquad
\tau_u = H_g(\tau_u^{struct}\parallel \tau_u^{ctx}),
\end{equation}
followed by randomized blinding
\begin{equation}
\tau'_u = \tau_u \cdot g^{r},
\end{equation}
and token generation
\begin{equation}
Tok_u = \textsf{ABSE.TokenGen}(SK_A,\tau'_u).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game 1 (PRF Replacement).}
Replace $F_{K_s}$ with a truly random function $\mathcal{R}$. By PRF
security,
\begin{equation}
|Pr[Game_0]-Pr[Game_1]| \leq \epsilon_1(\lambda).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game 2 (Random-Oracle Replacement).}
Model $H_g$ as a random oracle and replace $\tau_u$ by a uniformly
distributed element in $\mathbb{G}_1$ consistent with oracle outputs.
Then
\begin{equation}
|Pr[Game_1]-Pr[Game_2]| \leq \epsilon_2(\lambda).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game 3 (Randomized Tag Unlinkability).}
Because fresh randomness $r$ is chosen for each token,
\begin{equation}
\tau'_u = \tau_u g^{r},
\end{equation}
the adversary cannot link repeated queries by token equality. Any
advantage gained from distinguishing repeated tokens is bounded by
$\epsilon_3(\lambda)$.

\textbf{Game 4 (ABSE Reduction).}
Replace encrypted tags and corresponding token interactions with those
generated by the ABSE challenge oracle. If the adversary distinguishes
this game from the previous one, then it breaks the adaptive IND-CKA
security of ABSE. Hence
\begin{equation}
|Pr[Game_3]-Pr[Game_4]| \leq \epsilon_4(\lambda).
\end{equation}

\textbf{Game 5 (Ideal Leakage-Only Simulation).}
In the final game, trapdoors are simulated using only
$\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}$. Since all structural tags, contextual tags,
and token randomness have been replaced by random values consistent
with the allowed leakage, the adversary’s success probability is
exactly
\begin{equation}
Pr[Game_5]=\frac{1}{2}.
\end{equation}

Combining the hybrids gives
\begin{equation}
Adv_{\mathcal{A}}^{IND\text{-}CKA}
\leq
\epsilon_1(\lambda)+\epsilon_2(\lambda)+\epsilon_3(\lambda)+\epsilon_4(\lambda),
\end{equation}
which is negligible. Therefore, the scheme achieves adaptive search
privacy under leakage $\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{BVCRSA}}$.


\subsection{Theorem 3: Security Against a Compromised Edge Host}

\textbf{Statement.}
Assuming TEE confidentiality and integrity, any PPT adversary
$\mathcal{A}_{edge}$ controlling the edge host learns no plaintext
sensor value, contextual tuple, or intermediate BVCRSA state beyond
negligible probability.

\textbf{Proof.}
All sensitive operations are executed within the enclave. In
particular, device ciphertexts are decrypted only inside the TEE:
\begin{equation}
D = \textsf{AES\mbox{-}GCM.Dec}(K_{AES}^{(i)}, CT_{AES}^{(i)}),
\end{equation}
yielding
\begin{equation}
D=(m,k,t,v), \qquad ctx=(m,k,t),
\end{equation}
which never appear outside enclave memory.

Adaptive BVCRSA construction, interval-path updates, dual-layer tag
generation, bitmap masking, AHE encryption, and path-consistent
binding are all performed inside the enclave. Thus the host sees only
the externalized artifacts
\begin{equation}
\{CT_u^{tag}, \widetilde{B}_u, CT_v, Agg_u, Cnt_u, \sigma_u\}.
\end{equation}

Because
\begin{equation}
\widetilde{B}_u = \hat{B}_u \oplus F_{K_s}(ctx \parallel l_u \parallel r_u),
\end{equation}
the host cannot recover unmasked membership vectors without breaking
the PRF. Likewise, because
\begin{equation}
CT_v = \textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Enc}(P, v),
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
Agg_u = \sum CT_x,
\end{equation}
the host learns no plaintext values unless it breaks EC-ElGamal security.

Hence, if $\mathcal{A}_{edge}$ can recover plaintext or intermediate
state, it must either:
\begin{itemize}
\item break TEE confidentiality,
\item tamper with enclave execution without detection, or
\item break the underlying cryptographic assumptions.
\end{itemize}
All are ruled out by assumption. Therefore, edge security holds.


\subsection{Theorem 4: Access-Control Soundness and Collusion Resistance}

\textbf{Statement.}
Any PPT adversary whose attribute set does not satisfy access policy
$\mathcal{P}$ cannot generate a valid search token that matches
$CT_u^{tag}$, except with negligible probability.

\textbf{Proof.}
Each BVCRSA node tag is encrypted under policy $\mathcal{P}$:
\begin{equation}
CT_u^{tag} = \textsf{ABSE.Enc}(PP,\tau_u,\mathcal{P}).
\end{equation}
A user with attribute set $A$ receives
\begin{equation}
SK_A \leftarrow \textsf{ABSE.KeyGen}(MSK,A),
\end{equation}
and computes
\begin{equation}
Tok_u = \textsf{ABSE.TokenGen}(SK_A,\tau'_u).
\end{equation}
By correctness of ABSE,
\begin{equation}
\textsf{ABSE.Test}(PP,Tok_u,CT_u^{tag})=1
\quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad
A \models \mathcal{P}.
\end{equation}

Suppose an adversary with $A \not\models \mathcal{P}$ produces
$Tok^*$ such that
\begin{equation}
\textsf{ABSE.Test}(PP,Tok^*,CT_u^{tag})=1.
\end{equation}
Then the adversary has forged a valid token for a policy it does not
satisfy, which directly contradicts the security of the ABSE scheme.

For collusion, let $\{A_i\}$ be multiple users such that each
$A_i \not\models \mathcal{P}$ individually, but
$\bigcup_i A_i \models \mathcal{P}$. Because ABSE secret keys are bound
to their own randomness and identity-specific key components, simply
combining them cannot produce a valid token for $\mathcal{P}$ unless
the scheme’s collusion resistance is broken. Therefore, both
unauthorized access and collusion attacks succeed only with negligible
probability.


\subsection{Correctness Proposition: Query Evaluation and Aggregation}

\textbf{Statement.}
For any valid query
\begin{equation}
Q=(m,k,t,[a,b]),
\end{equation}
the proposed scheme returns exactly the aggregate of all encrypted
records whose value lies in $[a,b]$, whose context equals
$(m,k,t)$, and whose access policy is satisfied by the querying user.

\textbf{Proof.}
The proof follows from three properties.

\textbf{(i) Correct interval decomposition.}
The query range is decomposed into a canonical BVCRSA node cover
\begin{equation}
[a,b] \subseteq \bigcup_{u \in \mathcal{M}'} I_u,
\qquad
\forall u,v \in \mathcal{M}',\, u \neq v :
I_u \cap I_v = \emptyset.
\end{equation}
Hence every qualifying value is covered exactly once.

\textbf{(ii) Correct node selection.}
For each node in the cover, matching succeeds only when the encrypted
tag corresponds to the reconstructed query token and the requester’s
attributes satisfy the policy. Bitmap filtering further removes
non-matching candidates. Thus the final selected set $\mathcal{M}'$
contains exactly the nodes corresponding to
\begin{equation}
R_Q = \{x \mid x \in [a,b], \; ctx(x)=(m,k,t)\}.
\end{equation}

\textbf{(iii) Correct homomorphic aggregation.}
Each node maintains
\begin{equation}
Agg_u = \prod_{x \in Desc(u)} CT_x,
\qquad
Cnt_u = \textsf{Enc}(|Desc(u)|).
\end{equation}
Therefore,
\begin{equation}
CT_{sum}
=
\prod_{u \in \mathcal{M}'} Agg_u
=
\prod_{x \in R_Q} CT_x,
\end{equation}
and similarly
\begin{equation}
CT_{count}
=
\prod_{u \in \mathcal{M}'} Cnt_u.
\end{equation}
By correctness of AHE decryption,
\begin{equation}
\textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Dec}(x, CT_{sum})=\sum_{x \in R_Q} x,
\end{equation}
and
\begin{equation}
\textsf{EC\text{-}ElGamal.Dec}(x, CT_{count})=|R_Q|.
\end{equation}
Thus the returned result is correct, complete, and duplication-free.


\subsection{Theorem 6: Verifiable Aggregation Soundness and Completeness}

\textbf{Statement.}
Any modification, omission, duplication, or injection of node
aggregates by the cloud is detected with overwhelming probability,
assuming collision resistance of the underlying hash function.

\textbf{Proof.}

\textbf{(i) Node-level integrity.}
Each BVCRSA node is authenticated through a Merkle digest
\begin{equation}
h_u = H(ID_u \parallel Agg_u \parallel Cnt_u),
\end{equation}
and the cloud returns the corresponding authentication path $\pi_u$.
The user checks
\begin{equation}
\textsf{Verify}(Root,u,Agg_u,Cnt_u,\pi_u)=1.
\end{equation}
Any modification to $Agg_u$ or $Cnt_u$ changes $h_u$ and invalidates
the proof unless the adversary finds a hash collision.

\textbf{(ii) Path-consistent binding.}
The binding
\begin{equation}
\sigma_u = H(\tau_u \parallel CT_v \parallel \sigma_{parent(u)})
\end{equation}
cryptographically links each node’s encrypted value to its structural
position. Hence substitution of ciphertexts across BVCRSA nodes is
detectable unless $H$ is broken.

\textbf{(iii) Aggregation commitment.}
The cloud computes
\begin{equation}
\Pi_{agg}
=
H\big(
Root \parallel \mathcal{M}' \parallel CT_{sum} \parallel CT_{count}
\big).
\end{equation}
Because $\mathcal{M}'$ is the deterministically derived disjoint node
set contributing to the query, any omission, duplication, or injection
changes the commitment input and causes verification failure.

Therefore:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Soundness} holds because no forged or modified aggregate
can pass verification without breaking collision resistance.
\item \textbf{Completeness} holds because omission of any valid node or
duplication of any node changes $\Pi_{agg}$ and is thus detected.
\end{itemize}

Hence verifiable aggregation is achieved with overwhelming
probability.






