\subsection{Comparison of System Functions}
In this section, we conduct a comprehensive functional comparison between the proposed BVCRSA framework and several state-of-the-art schemes: EPBRQ \cite{ref34}, EPRQ+ \cite{ref35}, MHRQ \cite{ref37}, and Trinity \cite{ref39}. The comparison is summarized in Table \ref{tab:functional_comparison}.

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Search Logic and Efficiency:} Existing schemes utilize various structures to handle range queries. MHRQ \cite{ref37} uses a singly linked list for healthcare data, which may result in linear search overhead during frequent updates. Trinity \cite{ref39} introduces a scalable Quotient Filter for spatio-temporal data to achieve sub-linear efficiency. EPRQ+ \cite{ref35} employs a binary tree-based index using Range Encode (REncoder) for faster retrieval. Our proposed \textit{BVCRSA} scheme further optimizes this by integrating a \textit{Bitmap-assisted Range-Cover Tree}, allowing the Cloud to skip irrelevant sub-trees and achieve logarithmic search complexity without false positives.

    \item \textbf{Security and Privacy:} Trinity \cite{ref39} and MHRQ \cite{ref37} focus on forward and backward privacy. EPRQ+ \cite{ref35} utilizes Additional Symmetric-key Hidden Vector Encryption (ASHVE) to hide index lengths. While EPBRQ \cite{ref34} protects spatial privacy via secure kNN, it lacks fine-grained access control. Our framework integrates \textit{Attribute-Based Searchable Encryption (ABSE)}, ensuring that search trapdoors are cryptographically bound to specific authorized attributes.

    \item \textbf{Data Analytics and Aggregation:} A major limitation of the compared schemes \cite{ref34, ref35, ref37, ref39} is that they are primarily designed for data retrieval and do not support computation over encrypted values. By incorporating \textit{Additive Homomorphic Encryption (AHE)}, specifically EC-ElGamal over the NIST P-256 curve, our system enables the Cloud server to perform summations and statistical aggregations directly on ciphertexts.
\end{itemize}

