As presented in Table~IV, the proposed scheme demonstrates improved computational efficiency across index generation, trapdoor construction, and query processing compared with existing approaches. In MHRQ~\cite{ref37}, index construction relies on direct hashing over all records, resulting in a linear complexity of $O(n)T_{hash}$. EPRQ+~\cite{ref35} further increases this cost by introducing structured SHVE-based encoding, leading to $O(n \log n)T_{SHVE}$ due to hierarchical operations. In contrast, the proposed scheme offloads index generation to the edge node and employs lightweight salted hashing, yielding an effective complexity of $O(n' \log N)T_{hash}$, where $n'$ denotes the batch size processed at the edge. This design significantly reduces the client-side burden and improves scalability for large datasets. 

For trapdoor generation, existing schemes such as EPRQ+~\cite{ref35} and Trinity~\cite{ref39} rely on vector-based encryption, incurring a cost proportional to the query range width, i.e., $O(m)T_{SHVE}$, which becomes inefficient for wide-range queries. The proposed scheme instead adopts an ABSE-based construction, where trapdoors are generated through matrix operations with complexity $O(k)T_{matrix}$, where $k$ is the number of query attributes. This approach decouples the computational cost from the range size, resulting in more stable and efficient trapdoor generation. 

During query processing, MHRQ~\cite{ref37} performs linear traversal over the dataset, leading to $O(n)$ complexity. By contrast, the proposed scheme leverages the BVCRSA-based hierarchical tree structure to enable logarithmic partitioning of the search space. As a result, query processing achieves $O(m \log N)$ complexity, where $m$ denotes the number of matched nodes, thereby significantly reducing search overhead while supporting precise and expressive range queries.

\subsection{Experimental Setup}

To validate the practical performance of the proposed BVCRSA framework, we conduct comprehensive experiments comparing it against six state-of-the-art privacy-preserving range query schemes: MHRQ~\cite{ref37}, Trinity~\cite{ref39}, ABSE-Range~\cite{ref41}, and ECGRQ~\cite{ref44}.

\textbf{Implementation.} All schemes are implemented in Python~3.12 using real cryptographic primitives. BVCRSA employs BN128 bilinear pairings via the \texttt{py\_ecc} library for ABSE and NIST P-256 EC-ElGamal for additive homomorphic encryption. Trinity implements SHVE with Hilbert curve mapping and Quotient Filters. MHRQ uses CRQ matrix encryption with DPRF chains. ABSE-Range uses LSSS matrix with 0,1-coding for range encoding. ECGRQ uses a privacy-preserving learned index for conjunctive geometric range queries. No simulated or artificial delays are used in any benchmark.

All baseline schemes were re-implemented by the authors following original papers using identical cryptographic libraries (py\_ecc BN128, NIST P-256) normalized to 128-bit security. Cryptographic operation time is measured exclusively, excluding MongoDB I/O, averaged over 3 runs using \texttt{time.perf\_counter()}.

\textbf{Environment.} Experiments are conducted on a machine running Ubuntu Linux with Python~3.12. MongoDB Atlas (M0 cluster) serves as the cloud storage backend. All timing measurements use \texttt{time.perf\_counter()} for microsecond-precision wall-clock timing.

\textbf{Dataset.} We generate synthetic IIoT sensor data consisting of records $D = (m, k, t, v)$ with machine identifiers, sensor keywords drawn from a pool of 20 keyword types, hourly timestamps, and integer sensor values uniformly distributed in $[0, 100]$. To evaluate robustness under non-uniform data, we additionally test with sensor values drawn from a normal distribution $\mathcal{N}(70, 10)$, clipped to $[0, 100]$, simulating skewed real-world sensor readings concentrated around a typical operating point.

\textbf{Benchmark Dimensions.} Performance is evaluated along five independent dimensions:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Dimension~1 (Scalability):} Database size $N \in \{1\text{K}, 5\text{K}, 10\text{K}, 50\text{K}, 100\text{K}\}$ with fixed range $[35, 65]$ (30\% of domain) and 1 keyword.
\item \textbf{Dimension~2 (Range Width):} Range query size $\in \{10\%, 20\%, 30\%, 50\%, 80\%\}$ of the value domain with fixed $N = 10\text{K}$ and 1 keyword.
\item \textbf{Dimension~3 (Conjunctive Queries):} Number of query dimensions $d \in \{1, 2, 3, 5\}$ with fixed $N = 10\text{K}$ and range $[35, 65]$. ECGRQ is the primary conjunctive competitor.
\item \textbf{Dimension~4 (Aggregation):} Aggregation time vs.\ number of matched BVCRSA nodes $|B_Q| \in \{10, 50, 100, 500, 1000\}$.
\item \textbf{Dimension~5 (Verification):} Verification time vs.\ number of verified nodes $|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}| \in \{5, 10, 20, 50, 100\}$.
\end{itemize}

