    \caption{Aggregation time vs.\ number of matched BVCRSA nodes $|B_Q|$. EC-ElGamal point addition scales linearly with the number of aggregated nodes.}
    \label{fig:agg_vs_bq}
\end{figure}

Fig.~\ref{fig:agg_vs_bq} measures the homomorphic aggregation time as the number of matched BVCRSA nodes $|B_Q|$ increases from 10 to 1,000. Aggregation time scales linearly from 0.8\,ms ($|B_Q| = 10$) to 78\,ms ($|B_Q| = 1{,}000$), confirming that each EC-ElGamal point addition contributes constant overhead. This linear scaling is a direct consequence of the additive homomorphic property, where each node aggregate requires exactly one elliptic curve point addition per ciphertext component.

\subsubsection{Verification Time}

\begin{figure}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{fig_index_build_time.png}
    \caption{Verification time vs.\ number of verified nodes $|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}|$. Merkle proof verification and aggregation commitment checking scale linearly with the result set size.}
    \label{fig:verify_vs_uq}
\end{figure}

Fig.~\ref{fig:verify_vs_uq} evaluates verification time as the number of verified nodes $|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}|$ increases from 5 to 100. Verification time increases from 0.4\,ms ($|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}| = 5$) to 7.2\,ms ($|\mathcal{U}_Q^{*}| = 100$), comprising Merkle proof verification, path-consistent binding checks, and aggregation commitment validation. The $O(1)$ commitment validation dominates only at small result sets; at larger sets, per-node Merkle path verification ($O(\log N)$ per node) becomes the primary cost.

\subsubsection{Index Generation Time}

\begin{figure}[t]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{fig7_index_vs_N.png}
    \caption{Index generation time vs.\ database size $N$. BVCRSA incurs the highest index construction cost due to real BN128 bilinear pairing operations; however, this is a one-time offline cost.}
    \label{fig:index_vs_N}
\end{figure}

Fig.~\ref{fig:index_vs_N} shows the index generation time across all schemes. BVCRSA exhibits the highest index construction cost, scaling from 236\,s at $N = 1\text{K}$ to 23{,}600\,s at $N = 100\text{K}$. This overhead is attributable to BN128 bilinear pairing operations during ABSE encryption, which involves multiple scalar multiplications in $\mathbb{G}_1$ and $\mathbb{G}_2$ per BVCRSA node. ECGRQ incurs moderate index cost due to learned-index training ($\gamma$ prediction segments). Index construction is a \emph{one-time offline operation} performed at the edge during data ingestion. This cost is amortized over the dataset lifetime and does not affect online query latency.

\subsubsection{Skewed Distribution Evaluation}

To evaluate robustness under non-uniform data, we repeat the query processing benchmark (Dimension~1) with sensor values drawn from $\mathcal{N}(70, 10)$ instead of $\mathit{Uniform}(0, 100)$. Under skewed distribution, BVCRSA's query time increases by only 8--12\% compared to the uniform case, because the BVCRSA hierarchical decomposition adapts to data density through context-bound node construction. In contrast, MHRQ's volume-padding strategy causes 25--40\% overhead increase under skew, as padding must accommodate the concentrated value distribution. ECGRQ's learned index degrades by 15--22\% because its prediction model was trained on uniform assumptions. Trinity maintains comparable performance to the uniform case due to its Hilbert curve spatial mapping.

\subsubsection{Storage Overhead}

BVCRSA stores per-node metadata comprising the ABSE ciphertext ($CT_u^{tag}$, 256 bytes), masked bitmap ($\widetilde{B}_u$, 128 bytes), two EC-ElGamal ciphertext pairs ($Agg_u$, $Cnt_u$, 128 bytes total), and binding value ($\sigma_u$, 32 bytes), totaling 544 bytes per node. With three BVCRSA nodes per record, the storage overhead is approximately 1.6\,KB per record. MHRQ incurs 2.1$\times$ higher storage due to volume padding. ECGRQ requires 1.3$\times$ due to learned-index model parameters.

\subsection{Summary of Results}

The experimental evaluation demonstrates that BVCRSA achieves the best overall performance across the critical online operations:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Trapdoor generation:} BVCRSA achieves 0.03\,ms (constant), independent of database size, range width, and number of dimensions.
\item \textbf{Query processing:} BVCRSA achieves 612\,ms at $N = 100\text{K}$, representing a 6--12$\times$ improvement over all compared schemes, enabled by the hierarchical BVCRSA decomposition with $O(\log |D_v|)$ complexity sublinear in domain size.
\item \textbf{Conjunctive queries:} BVCRSA scales linearly with dimension count $d$ through independent per-dimension processing, outperforming ECGRQ at $d \geq 3$.
\item \textbf{Aggregation and verification:} EC-ElGamal aggregation and Merkle-based verification both scale linearly with result set size, remaining under 78\,ms and 7.2\,ms respectively for realistic workloads.
\item \textbf{Skewed data:} BVCRSA degrades by only 8--12\% under $\mathcal{N}(70,10)$ distribution, demonstrating robustness to non-uniform sensor data.
\item \textbf{Index construction:} While BVCRSA incurs the highest offline indexing cost due to real BN128 pairings, this is a one-time operation that enables the demonstrated superior online performance.
\end{itemize}

These results validate that the proposed framework effectively bridges the gap between security and efficiency, making it suitable for large-scale privacy-preserving IIoT range query and aggregation scenarios.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

This paper presented a privacy-preserving framework for secure range queries and aggregate analytics over encrypted IIoT sensor data. The proposed system integrates attribute-based searchable encryption (ABSE) using BN128 bilinear pairings for fine-grained access-controlled search, lifted EC-ElGamal over the NIST P-256 curve for additive homomorphic aggregation, and a novel Bitmap-Verified Conjunctive Range-cover Secure Aggregation (BVCRSA) for efficient hierarchical index organization.

The BVCRSA structure enables query processing sublinear in domain size with $O(\log |D_v|)$ complexity by decomposing range queries into a minimal set of disjoint interval nodes, each maintaining encrypted aggregate summaries. The dual-layer context-bound tagging mechanism ensures query isolation across contexts, while the PRF-based masked bitmap filtering mitigates frequency and correlation leakage. A lightweight structure-aware aggregation commitment provides verifiable correctness without relying on expensive zero-knowledge proofs.

Security analysis demonstrates that the scheme achieves payload confidentiality under the IND-CPA security of EC-ElGamal, adaptive search privacy under the IND-CKA security of ABSE, edge security via TEE confinement, and access-control soundness with collusion resistance. Comprehensive experimental evaluation against six state-of-the-art schemes (EPBRQ, EPRQ+, MHRQ, Trinity, ABSE-Range, and ECGRQ) across database sizes up to $N = 100\text{K}$ confirms that BVCRSA achieves the lowest trapdoor generation time ($\sim$0.03\,ms, constant) and query processing time (6--12$\times$ faster than competitors), while the higher offline index construction cost is justified as a one-time edge-side operation that enables superior online performance.

Future work includes optimizing the BN128 pairing operations through batch processing and precomputation to reduce index construction time, extending the framework to support dynamic data updates with forward and backward privacy, and investigating multi-authority ABSE constructions for decentralized IIoT environments.

